First we show that if a set $S \subset \mathbb{Z}$ satisfies the conditions then $|S| \ge \frac{n}{2} + 1$. Let $d = [n/2]$, so $n \le 2d \le n + 1$. In order to prove that $|S| \ge d + 1$, construct a graph as follows. Let the vertices of the graph be the elements of $S$. For each $1 \le k \le d$, choose two elements $x, y \in S$ such that $x - y = F_{2k-1}$, and add the pair $(x, y)$ to the graph as edge. (Note that by the problem's constraints, there must be a pair $(x, y)$ with $x - y = F_{2k-1}$ for every $3 \le 2k-1 \le 2d-1 \le n$; moreover, due to $F_1 = F_2$ we have a pair with $x - y = F_1$ as well. ) We will say that the length of the edge $(x, y)$ is $|x - y|$.

We claim that the graph contains no cycle. For the sake of contradiction, suppose that the graph contains a cycle $(x_1, \dots, x_\ell)$, and let the longest edge in the cycle be $(x_1, x_\ell)$ with length $F_{2m+1}$. The other edges $(x_1, x_2), \dots, (x_{\ell-1}, x_\ell)$ in the cycle are shorter than $F_{2m+1}$ and distinct, their lengths form a subset of $\{F_1, F_3, \dots, F_{2m-1}\}$. But this is not possible because

$$
\begin{align*} 
F_{2m+1} &= |x_{\ell} - x_1| \le \sum_{i=1}^{\ell-1} |x_{i+1} - x_i| \le F_1 + F_3 + F_5 + \dots + F_{2m-1} \\ 
&= F_2 + (F_4 - F_2) + (F_6 - F_4) + \dots + (F_{2m} - F_{2m-2}) = F_{2m} < F_{2m+1} 
\end{align*}
$$

Hence, the graph has $d$ edges and cannot contain a cycle, therefore it must contain at least $d+1$ vertices, so $|S| \ge d+1$. Now we show a suitable set with $d+1$ elements. Let

$$
S = \{F_0, F_2, F_4, F_5, \dots, F_{2d}\}
$$

For $1 \le k \le d$ we have $F_0, F_{2k-2}, F_{2k} \in S$ with differences $F_{2k} - F_{2k-2} = F_{2k-1}$ and $F_{2k} - F_0 = F_{2k}$, so each of $F_1, F_2, \dots, F_{2d}$ occurs as difference between two elements in $S$. So this set containing $d+1$ numbers is suitable. \u25a1
